---
import Layout from '../../layouts/Layout.astro';
import BrandBranchesGrid from '../../components/BrandBranchesGrid.astro';
import { MAIN_PHONE, MAIN_PHONE_TEL } from '../../data/branches';

const title = "Miele Dishwasher Repair Los Angeles — Same Day";
const description = "Miele dishwasher repair across SoCal. G 7000 AutoDos, G 5000 Discovery, Futura, and integrated panel-ready models. $89 dx waived.";

const schemaJsons = [
  {
    "@context": "https://schema.org",
    "@type": "LocalBusiness",
    "@id": "https://samedayappliance.repair/brands/miele-dishwasher-repair/#business",
    "name": "Same Day Appliance Repair, Miele Dishwasher Service",
    "image": "https://samedayappliance.repair/images/same-day-appliance-repair.png",
    "url": "https://samedayappliance.repair/brands/miele-dishwasher-repair/",
    "telephone": MAIN_PHONE_TEL,
    "priceRange": "$$$$"
  },
  {
    "@context": "https://schema.org",
    "@type": "Service",
    "serviceType": "Miele Dishwasher Repair",
    "provider": { "@type": "LocalBusiness", "name": "Same Day Appliance Repair" },
    "areaServed": [
      { "@type": "AdministrativeArea", "name": "Los Angeles County" },
      { "@type": "AdministrativeArea", "name": "Orange County" },
      { "@type": "AdministrativeArea", "name": "Ventura County" },
      { "@type": "AdministrativeArea", "name": "San Bernardino County" },
      { "@type": "AdministrativeArea", "name": "Riverside County" }
    ],
    "offers": {
      "@type": "Offer",
      "priceSpecification": {
        "@type": "PriceSpecification",
        "price": "89.00",
        "priceCurrency": "USD",
        "description": "Diagnostic fee, waived with repair"
      }
    }
  },
  {
    "@context": "https://schema.org",
    "@type": "FAQPage",
    "mainEntity": [
      {
        "@type": "Question",
        "name": "What does fault code F11 mean on my Miele dishwasher?",
        "acceptedAnswer": {
          "@type": "Answer",
          "text": "F11 is a drainage fault, the dishwasher cannot empty water from the cabinet. Per Miele service documentation (G 7xxx and G 5xxx Discovery from 2019 onward), causes in diagnostic order: filter combination in the cabinet blocked (rinse under running water, free), drain pump impeller broken or blocked by debris, non-return valve ball in the sump jammed, drain hose kinked behind the unit, or (rarer) drain pump motor failed. F11 also registers as a secondary code if the heater relay doesn't activate after an F51 register check. We diagnose the whole path: filter, impeller, hose, sump, then pump. 70% resolve at the filter or impeller without parts."
        }
      },
      {
        "@type": "Question",
        "name": "What does fault code F24 mean?",
        "acceptedAnswer": {
          "@type": "Answer",
          "text": "F24 is a heater relay error, the relay that switches the heating element on and off is malfunctioning. Four causes: faulty heater relay on the control board, wiring between relay and heating element degraded, heating element itself open-circuit (less common), or the main control board has an issue affecting relay operation. Diagnostic: test heating element continuity (should read 20-30 ohms), test relay with a meter on the control board, inspect wire harness for burn marks. Relay replacement typically means control board replacement ($580-$820) since the relay is board-mounted on G 7000 series. Heating element replacement $285-$420. We verify which before ordering."
        }
      },
      {
        "@type": "Question",
        "name": "F52 error code, what's happening?",
        "acceptedAnswer": {
          "@type": "Answer",
          "text": "F52 means the sensor has detected excess foam in the cabinet and interrupted the program as a protection measure. Cause is almost always wrong detergent: regular dish soap or too much detergent, combi tablets used without activating Combi Tablet Program, or generic detergent that foams more than the Miele-spec profile. Fix: turn selector to Stop/Finish, press Start/Stop 1 second to stop flashing LED, power cycle the dishwasher. If using combi tablets, set the Combi Tablet Program in the menu. If using Miele AutoDos with PowerDisk, no additional detergent should be added. Avoid Quick Wash 40°C with combi tablets, it's a specific incompatibility. After remediation, no parts typically needed."
        }
      },
      {
        "@type": "Question",
        "name": "Random F79 error, Miele won't start",
        "acceptedAnswer": {
          "@type": "Answer",
          "text": "F79 is an electrical supply fault, specifically, the dishwasher detects frequency or voltage anomalies on the circuit. In LA luxury kitchens, we see this most often when the dishwasher shares a circuit or adjacent circuit with Lutron Caseta or similar dimmer-controlled lighting (under-cabinet LED strips, kitchen pendants, island lights). The dimmer's phase-cut waveform can feed electrical noise back through shared neutrals or from adjacent circuits and the Miele control rejects it. Solutions: verify the dishwasher is on its own dedicated 20A circuit (code-required anyway), move or remove the interfering dimmer if the circuit is shared, or install a line filter between breaker and appliance. On confirmed circuit-isolation fixes, the F79 doesn't recur."
        }
      },
      {
        "@type": "Question",
        "name": "F600 or F601 error on my G 7000 AutoDos",
        "acceptedAnswer": {
          "@type": "Answer",
          "text": "F600/F601/F607 are AutoDos dispensing faults, specific to G 7000 series with the PowerDisk automatic detergent system. Common causes: PowerDisk not seated correctly in its holder (pull and reseat, free fix), PowerDisk near-empty (replace, available from Miele USA or Amazon for ~$25), dispensing outlet partially blocked with hardened detergent residue (wipe with warm water and soft cloth), or the AutoDos motor itself has failed (replacement $245-$340, 60-minute job). We start with the PowerDisk reseat since it fixes 40% of these codes immediately without parts."
        }
      },
      {
        "@type": "Question",
        "name": "How much does Miele dishwasher repair cost?",
        "acceptedAnswer": {
          "@type": "Answer",
          "text": "Diagnostic is $89, waived with repair. Typical Miele dishwasher repairs: drain pump $185-$285, circulation pump $385-$540, water inlet valve (AquaStop) $245-$345, heater element $285-$420, door lock/interlock $165-$245, door gasket $145-$215, turbidity sensor $185-$265, AutoDos motor $245-$340, flow meter $95-$155, main control board $580-$820, PowerDisk dispenser assembly $165-$240, decalcifier/salt reservoir $145-$215. Labor and parts quoted before work starts."
        }
      }
    ]
  }
];
---
<Layout title={title} description={description}>
  <Fragment slot="head-scripts">
    {schemaJsons.map((schema) => (
      <script type="application/ld+json" set:html={JSON.stringify(schema)} />
    ))}
  </Fragment>

  <section class="hero">
    <div class="hero-inner">
      <div class="hero-content">
        <p class="hero-eyebrow">LA · Orange · Ventura · San Bernardino · Riverside Counties</p>
        <h1>Miele Dishwasher Repair</h1>
        <p class="hero-sub">G 7000 AutoDos with PowerDisk, G 5000 Discovery, Futura Series, and integrated panel-ready models. Fault code diagnosis F11 through F79, F170s, F600s AutoDos codes. AquaStop leak protection, 3D MultiFlex tray, circulation and drain pump service. Factory-trained on every Miele dishwasher generation since 2012.</p>
        <div class="hero-ctas">
          <a href={`tel:${MAIN_PHONE_TEL}`} class="btn-primary">☎ {MAIN_PHONE}</a>
          <a href="/contact/" class="btn-outline">Book Online</a>
        </div>
      </div>
      <div class="hero-img-wrap">
        <div class="hero-img-placeholder">
          <p>Miele Dishwasher Repair</p>
          <p>Across Southern California</p>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <div class="trust-bar">
    <div class="trust-bar-inner">
      <div class="trust-item"><span class="trust-icon">🏅</span> BHGS #A49573</div>
      <div class="trust-item"><span class="trust-icon">🛡</span> Fully Insured</div>
      <div class="trust-item"><span class="trust-icon">⚡</span> Same Day Available</div>
      <div class="trust-item"><span class="trust-icon">🔩</span> OEM Parts on Truck</div>
      <div class="trust-item"><span class="trust-icon">💬</span> $89 Diagnostic, Waived With Repair</div>
    </div>
  </div>

  <!-- ── INTRO ── -->
  <section class="section">
    <div class="container narrow">
      <p class="eyebrow-sub">About this service</p>
      <h2>Miele's reference dishwasher deserves reference-level service.</h2>
      <p>The Miele G 7000 is the reference standard in residential dishwashers. AutoDos with the PowerDisk cartridge dispenses detergent automatically for each cycle, no pods, no measuring, no residue around the dispenser. AquaStop provides full leak protection with both a primary shut-off at the inlet hose and a secondary float sensor in the base pan that cuts power if water reaches the cabinet floor. The 3D MultiFlex middle rack adjusts in three axes, height, width, depth, to fit baking sheets and oversized serving pieces that don't fit in conventional dishwashers. AutoOpen automatically cracks the door open at cycle end for residual-heat drying. QuickPowerWash finishes a full wash-rinse-dry in 58 minutes when you need glasses back for a dinner party.</p>
      <p>All of that engineering means two things for service. First: the diagnostic protocols are detailed and the fault codes are specific, an F11 tells us it's a drainage fault with a defined sequence of suspect components, not a generic "dishwasher not working." Second: the platform is complex enough that generic dishwasher technicians routinely miss the real cause. We see second-opinion calls where a prior tech swapped a drain pump on an F11 code when the actual issue was a blocked filter combination (free fix) or a jammed non-return valve ball in the sump (30-minute cleanup). Reading the codes correctly cuts service time and saves the owner money.</p>
      <p>Most of our Miele dishwasher calls come from districts where Miele was specified as the integrated panel-ready dishwasher, Bel Air, Beverly Hills, Brentwood, Pacific Palisades, Malibu, West Hollywood, and the Wilshire Corridor on LA's Westside; Newport Beach, Laguna Beach, and Irvine in Orange County; Westlake Village and Thousand Oaks in Ventura; and Murrieta and Temecula estate kitchens in Riverside County. These are units 3-to-12 years old, past the 2-year Miele USA warranty, running well overall but occasionally needing component-level service. Almost all our Miele dishwasher calls close same-visit.</p>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- ── MODELS ── -->
  <section class="section section-alt">
    <div class="container">
      <p class="eyebrow-sub">Platforms and models</p>
      <h2>Every Miele dishwasher generation we service</h2>

      <div class="model-grid">
        <div class="model-card">
          <h3>G 7000 Series (Current Flagship)</h3>
          <p class="model-list">G 7966 SCVi AutoDos · G 7966 SCVi · G 7566 SCVi · G 7316 SCU · G 7104 SCU · G 7966 SCVi XXL</p>
          <p>Current Miele flagship with AutoDos automatic dispensing via PowerDisk cartridge, AquaStop full leak protection, 3D MultiFlex middle rack, QuickPowerWash 58-minute cycle, AutoOpen drying. Fault code structure uses F11-F79 plus F170s (TwinDos) and F600s (AutoDos). Most luxury kitchen specs across our service area for 2020+.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="model-card">
          <h3>G 5000 Series Discovery (2019-onward)</h3>
          <p class="model-list">G 5056 SCVi · G 5266 SCVi · G 5366 SCVi · G 5008 SCU · G 5226 SCU</p>
          <p>Mid-tier platform, same core Miele reliability and AutoOpen drying, without AutoDos (uses manual detergent dispenser). Still has AquaStop, 3D MultiFlex, heater system. F11-F79 fault codes apply, no F600 AutoDos codes. Common across our service area in new-construction mid-range luxury (Westside LA, Newport Beach, Irvine, Thousand Oaks, Rancho Cucamonga) around $1,500-$1,800 price point.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="model-card">
          <h3>G 4000 / G 6000 Series (2018-2022)</h3>
          <p class="model-list">G 4720 SCi · G 4925 SCU · G 6100 SCU · G 6200 SCU · G 6410 SCi</p>
          <p>Previous-generation mid-tier and flagship platforms. Standard F1-F79 fault codes apply. No AutoDos or F600 codes. Parts availability excellent from Miele USA distribution, we routinely service 5-to-7-year-old G 4000 and G 6000 units. Many luxury condos from 2018-2020 have these.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="model-card">
          <h3>Legacy Futura Series (pre-2018)</h3>
          <p class="model-list">G 2432 SCU · G 2832 SCi · G 5105 SCU · G 5575 SCSF</p>
          <p>Older Futura platforms from 2012-2017. Still common across Southern California kitchens installed during the 2015-era luxury remodel boom, Westside LA, Newport Beach, Westlake Village, and Temecula corridor. Parts mostly available but some legacy control boards require longer lead time. 10+ year old Futura units are typically on original pumps and motors, economics favor repair for any component-level failure.</p>
        </div>
      </div>

      <p class="footnote">Integrated PG8000 professional series (commercial dishwashers sometimes installed in residential butler's pantries), hidden LED panel, codes appear only with door ajar, reset via Start + Programme hold. We service residential installs of PG units case-by-case.</p>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- ── ERROR CODES TABLE ── -->
  <section class="section">
    <div class="container narrow">
      <p class="eyebrow-sub">Miele fault codes</p>
      <h2>Reading Miele dishwasher fault codes, decoder table</h2>
      <p>Miele dishwashers display specific F-codes that map directly to component faults. The OEM service manual structure is well-documented; we carry the full reference on every call. Here's the decoder for the most common codes you'll see on G 7000, G 5000 Discovery, and G 6000 units.</p>
      <table class="price-table">
        <thead>
          <tr><th>Code</th><th>Meaning &amp; common cause</th></tr>
        </thead>
        <tbody>
          <tr><td><strong>F11</strong></td><td>Drainage fault, filter blocked, drain pump impeller broken, non-return valve jammed, drain hose kinked</td></tr>
          <tr><td><strong>F12 / F13 / F14 / F15</strong></td><td>Water inlet fault, stopcock closed, inlet filter clogged, inlet hose kinked, water pressure below 0.3 bar (4.4 psi)</td></tr>
          <tr><td><strong>F18 / F19</strong></td><td>Inlet-related secondary faults</td></tr>
          <tr><td><strong>F24</strong></td><td>Heater relay error, relay on control board malfunctioning, wiring degraded, heating element open</td></tr>
          <tr><td><strong>F25 / F26</strong></td><td>Heater-related secondary faults</td></tr>
          <tr><td><strong>F33 / F36 / F38</strong></td><td>Spray arm blocked, dish obstruction, water flow restriction</td></tr>
          <tr><td><strong>F40 / F42 / F47</strong></td><td>Temperature sensor / NTC faults</td></tr>
          <tr><td><strong>F51 / F52 / F53</strong></td><td>Heater pressure switch, F52 is excess foam from wrong detergent, F51/F53 are circulation pump pressure issues</td></tr>
          <tr><td><strong>F63 / F67 / F68 / F69</strong></td><td>Circulation pump faults, pump motor, impeller, or start relay</td></tr>
          <tr><td><strong>F70</strong></td><td>Waterproof/AquaStop triggered, base pan sensor detected water, full leak-protection cutoff engaged</td></tr>
          <tr><td><strong>F78 / F79</strong></td><td>Electrical supply fault, frequency/voltage anomaly, often from shared dimmer circuits in luxury homes across our service area</td></tr>
          <tr><td><strong>F84 / F85 / F86 / F87 / F88</strong></td><td>Various control / communication faults</td></tr>
          <tr><td><strong>F170 / F171 / F172 / F173 / F177 / F179</strong></td><td>TwinDos / AutoDos dosing faults (G 7xxx from 2023+)</td></tr>
          <tr><td><strong>F600 / F601 / F607</strong></td><td>AutoDos dispensing outlet fault, PowerDisk seating, outlet blocked, or dispensing motor failed</td></tr>
        </tbody>
      </table>
      <p>Power-cycle reset (turn off at breaker for 60 seconds) clears transient codes. Persistent codes after a full cycle reset indicate an actual hardware fault and need service. About 40% of codes we see resolve at the filter/cleanup level without parts; 45% need a single component replacement; 15% need control board work.</p>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- ── COMMON PROBLEMS ── -->
  <section class="section section-alt">
    <div class="container">
      <p class="eyebrow-sub">Common failures</p>
      <h2>The nine things that break on a Miele dishwasher</h2>

      <div class="problem">
        <h3>1. Won't drain, F11 flashing, water pools in bottom</h3>
        <p>Drainage fault. Diagnostic order: remove lower spray arm, lift out filter combination, rinse under running water (fixes 50% of F11 immediately, no parts). If code persists: inspect drain pump impeller for debris or broken blades ($185-$285 replacement), check non-return valve ball in the sump for jamming (free cleanup), straighten drain hose behind the unit, test drain pump motor for continuity. We carry G 7000 and G 5000 drain pumps on the truck.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="problem">
        <h3>2. Won't fill with water, F12/F13/F14/F15 flashing</h3>
        <p>Water inlet fault. Check stopcock at the supply (often behind a cabinet kick panel), clean the inlet-hose mesh filter (free), verify water pressure at the tap (must be above 0.3 bar / 4.4 psi, LA homes with tankless water heaters sometimes run low). If all external paths check fine, the inlet valve (AquaStop) is failed, replacement $245-$345. On newer G 7000 units with AquaStop, the valve and the flood sensor are integrated; we verify the sensor hasn't tripped before swapping the valve.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="problem">
        <h3>3. F52, excess foam, cycle interrupted</h3>
        <p>Wrong detergent. Common causes: regular dish soap used by mistake, generic combi tablets without activating Combi Tablet Program in the menu, AutoDos PowerDisk plus additional manual detergent (double-dosing). Fix: turn off, power cycle, select Combi Tablet Program in the menu if using tablets, or remove the extra detergent. No parts needed. Hard-water districts (most of Southern California, particularly the Inland Empire) sometimes trigger F52 from rinse-aid over-dosing, recalibrate rinse aid dosing setting via the menu.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="problem">
        <h3>4. F24, heater relay error, no hot wash</h3>
        <p>Dishes come out cold and coated with detergent residue because water never heated. Cause: heater relay on the control board (most common), wiring harness to the heating element, or heating element open-circuit. Heating element tests 20-30 ohms good. On G 7000 the heater relay is board-mounted, if it's the relay, we replace the main control board ($580-$820). Heating element alone is $285-$420. We test both before ordering.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="problem">
        <h3>5. F70, AquaStop triggered, unit locked out</h3>
        <p>Water detected in the base pan. AquaStop's leak protection is working as designed, it cut power to prevent flooding. Root cause is almost always a real leak: degraded door gasket ($145-$215), circulation pump seal ($385-$540 for pump, or gasket alone if catchable), loose hose clamp inside the cabinet, or cracked sump housing (rare, $380+ replacement). We find the leak before resetting AquaStop, otherwise it re-triggers on the next cycle.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="problem">
        <h3>6. F600/F601, AutoDos dispensing fault (G 7000 only)</h3>
        <p>PowerDisk system fault. In order: reseat the PowerDisk (40% of these codes resolve with reseat), replace near-empty PowerDisk (owner typically has spares, Miele USA or Amazon ~$25 each), clean dispensing outlet with warm water and soft cloth (hardened detergent residue blocks flow), test AutoDos motor ($245-$340 replacement). We diagnose which before ordering the motor.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="problem">
        <h3>7. F79, electrical fault, won't start</h3>
        <p>Electrical supply anomaly, frequency or voltage outside spec. In LA luxury kitchens, we see this most often when the dishwasher shares a circuit or adjacent circuit with Lutron Caseta or similar dimmer-controlled lighting. Dimmer phase-cut noise couples into the Miele control and it rejects startup. Fixes: verify dishwasher is on a dedicated 20A circuit (code requirement anyway), relocate interfering dimmer, or install a line filter. On confirmed isolation fixes, F79 doesn't recur.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="problem">
        <h3>8. Dishes not drying, AutoOpen not opening, or wet after cycle</h3>
        <p>Three possibilities. AutoOpen latch motor failed, door doesn't crack open at cycle end. Turbidity sensor drifted, dishwasher thinks load is cleaner than it is, skips extended heat phase. Heater working but thermostat drifted, water not getting hot enough. AutoOpen latch $185, turbidity sensor $185-$265, thermostat $135. On G 7000 F28 drying codes are sometimes resolved via Miele@mobile app firmware update (no parts, no service visit), we check firmware version first.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="problem">
        <h3>9. Circulation pump noise, grinding, whining (F63/F67/F68/F69)</h3>
        <p>Circulation pump end-of-life. Grinding noise starts quiet and gets progressively worse over weeks. Sometimes preceded by reduced wash effectiveness (spray arms not spinning strongly). Pump replacement $385-$540, 90-minute job. On 10+ year old Miele dishwashers, we check the motor mount and impeller shaft alongside the pump, worn bearings in the host motor accelerate new-pump wear if not addressed.</p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- ── SOCAL HARD WATER ── -->
  <section class="section">
    <div class="container narrow">
      <p class="eyebrow-sub">Southern California context</p>
      <h2>Why Southern California hard water matters for Miele dishwasher service</h2>
      <p>SoCal tap water runs hard across all five counties we serve, typically 200-350 ppm calcium and magnesium in LA Westside districts, 250-400 ppm across most of Orange County, and 300-450+ ppm in the Inland Empire (Rancho Cucamonga, Temecula, Riverside) where Colorado River and groundwater blends drive hardness still higher. All of that is well above the 80-120 ppm that most European dishwashers were originally designed for. Miele handles this better than most brands because they include a water softener (the salt reservoir uses ion-exchange resin to soften water before it enters the wash cycle), but the softener has to be set correctly for local hardness. Many SoCal homeowners never adjust it from the factory default of 15°dH (German standard), which is too low for 250+ ppm water and badly undersized for IE hardness levels.</p>
      <p>What happens when the softener is underset: calcium deposits build up on the heater element (reducing heating efficiency and eventually triggering F24 codes), in the spray arms (blocking nozzles, reducing wash performance), and on glassware (the cloudy etched-glass film customers complain about). Descaling with Miele-branded descaling agent every 6 months is the right maintenance, but the real fix is adjusting the water-softener setting to 25°dH or 30°dH for LA/OC/Ventura water (and 35-40°dH for IE) and refilling salt every 2-3 months instead of the default 4-6, every 6-8 weeks in the IE.</p>
      <p>On every Miele dishwasher service call, we verify: current water-softener setting vs. local hardness (TDS meter test, 30 seconds), salt reservoir level, rinse aid dosing setting, and whether descaling is overdue. Adjusting these takes no time and parts and prevents the next service call 6 months out. We also recommend a salt refill schedule to the owner so they know when to top it up.</p>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- ── PRICING ── -->
  <section class="section section-alt">
    <div class="container narrow">
      <p class="eyebrow-sub">Pricing</p>
      <h2>What Miele dishwasher repair usually costs</h2>
      <p>Diagnostic $89, waived with repair. Labor and parts quoted separately before work starts.</p>
